1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,000
So

2
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,780
this week Vladimir Putin in

3
00:00:04,780 --> 00:00:08,000
a speech said to his Russian people

4
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,420
that

5
00:00:09,420 --> 00:00:12,940
all of Russia must now

6
00:00:12,940 --> 00:00:15,460
prepare for total war.

7
00:00:16,080 --> 00:00:21,140
Even if you are not fighting
on the front lines in Ukraine,

8
00:00:21,520 --> 00:00:22,800
pretend you are.

9
00:00:23,900 --> 00:00:27,500
And because of this speech,
there are many analysts

10
00:00:27,500 --> 00:00:28,740
who believe that

11
00:00:28,740 --> 00:00:33,140
Putin is preparing Russia for total war.

12
00:00:33,320 --> 00:00:35,360
And total war means that

13
00:00:35,360 --> 00:00:40,300
every aspect of your society is
geared towards winning a war.

14
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:44,380
And so we last had total
war in World War II, okay?

15
00:00:45,080 --> 00:00:46,600
But not after that.

16
00:00:47,100 --> 00:00:49,060
So why is Putin doing this?

17
00:00:49,540 --> 00:00:52,740
Now, there are some
people who believe that

18
00:00:52,740 --> 00:00:57,340
it's because Russia is not
doing so well in Ukraine.

19
00:00:57,620 --> 00:01:00,420
They lack manpower and so

20
00:01:00,420 --> 00:01:05,380
they need to mobilize their society
to fully win the war in Ukraine.

21
00:01:06,060 --> 00:01:08,840
Okay? Another explanation is

22
00:01:08,840 --> 00:01:11,980
that Putin knows

23
00:01:11,980 --> 00:01:13,000
that

24
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:18,400
NATO is preparing to send
reinforcements to Ukraine.

25
00:01:18,660 --> 00:01:22,580
Remember that because of
last summer's offensive,

26
00:01:22,740 --> 00:01:26,060
Ukraine is desperately short of manpower.

27
00:01:26,440 --> 00:01:31,360
Okay? The average age of their
soldiers right now is over 40.

28
00:01:31,500 --> 00:01:34,900
They have men in their 60s who
are fighting in the front lines.

29
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:41,420
Emmanuel Macron of France
has publicly stated

30
00:01:41,420 --> 00:01:43,940
that he is considering sending
French troops to Ukraine.

31
00:01:44,480 --> 00:01:48,100
The British themselves are
thinking of conscription,

32
00:01:48,220 --> 00:01:51,560
drafting all young men into the army.

33
00:01:51,560 --> 00:01:54,960
The American politicians have said

34
00:01:54,960 --> 00:01:57,420
that they're considering a new law that

35
00:01:57,420 --> 00:02:01,420
would give citizenship to illegal
immigrants who join the army.

36
00:02:01,660 --> 00:02:07,580
Okay? So it seems like NATO is only
going to escalate the war in Ukraine.

37
00:02:07,840 --> 00:02:09,200
And so Russia is preparing for that.

38
00:02:10,220 --> 00:02:13,400
One more explanation,
one more possibility is

39
00:02:13,400 --> 00:02:17,060
that Putin wants to expand the war.

40
00:02:17,240 --> 00:02:19,260
Okay? So he knows he's winning in Ukraine.

41
00:02:19,260 --> 00:02:22,880
He's thinking about attacking Moldova

42
00:02:22,880 --> 00:02:26,620
and possibly the Baltic states.

43
00:02:26,860 --> 00:02:29,560
Okay? These are all possibilities. Today,

44
00:02:29,900 --> 00:02:34,200
this morning, what I want to do
is argue another possibility,

45
00:02:34,460 --> 00:02:36,200
which is that

46
00:02:36,200 --> 00:02:41,760
Putin is mobilizing his society

47
00:02:41,760 --> 00:02:45,920
because he sees war as a tool,

48
00:02:46,180 --> 00:02:47,460
as a mechanism,

49
00:02:47,460 --> 00:02:50,740
to radically reshape

50
00:02:50,740 --> 00:02:53,740
the people in Russia.

51
00:02:55,160 --> 00:02:56,540
Okay? So think of a metaphor.

52
00:02:56,800 --> 00:02:58,860
Okay? You're fat and you're like, okay,

53
00:02:58,900 --> 00:03:02,500
how do I get fit?

54
00:03:02,800 --> 00:03:05,560
How do I get trim? Right? You
go to the gym and you work out.

55
00:03:07,140 --> 00:03:08,940
And for Putin, that's what war is.

56
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:12,220
War is a workout for society.

57
00:03:13,060 --> 00:03:16,860
When you enter war, you become a
much more disciplined, unified,

58
00:03:17,720 --> 00:03:19,500
and prosperous society.

59
00:03:21,200 --> 00:03:23,900
Okay? So that's what
I want to argue today.

60
00:03:24,480 --> 00:03:27,060
Okay. So why does Putin think like this?

61
00:03:27,220 --> 00:03:31,140
Well, let's look at the
current state of Russia.

62
00:03:31,400 --> 00:03:35,960
Okay? Russia, in many aspects,
is a broken society. Corruption.

63
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:42,900
Russia is the most corrupt
society in all of Europe.

64
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:45,840
The rich people, steal,

65
00:03:46,920 --> 00:03:50,380
and then they run off to Europe
or the United States or Dubai.

66
00:03:51,460 --> 00:03:56,360
Okay? So corruption is a
huge problem in Russia.

67
00:03:56,680 --> 00:04:02,320
And because of corruption,
the GDP of Russia is very low.

68
00:04:02,500 --> 00:04:06,440
So South Korea, which has about a
third of the population of Russia,

69
00:04:06,700 --> 00:04:08,420
has a higher GDP. Okay?

70
00:04:08,540 --> 00:04:13,120
The state of Texas, this one state in the
United States, has a higher GDP than Russia.

71
00:04:13,620 --> 00:04:17,800
So Russia, in many ways, in many
respects, is a very poor country.

72
00:04:18,040 --> 00:04:22,520
Okay? Second problem is alcoholism.

73
00:04:24,040 --> 00:04:27,300
One out of every six Russian males,

74
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:29,520
about 16, 17% of the population,

75
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:31,820
they're alcoholics.

76
00:04:31,880 --> 00:04:34,620
Okay? It's a disease.

77
00:04:34,860 --> 00:04:36,740
They have the disease of alcoholism.

78
00:04:37,920 --> 00:04:41,640
One out of every three deaths in Russia is

79
00:04:41,640 --> 00:04:43,780
because of drinking too much.

80
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:46,680
And because of alcoholism,

81
00:04:46,960 --> 00:04:51,820
the rate of young men

82
00:04:51,820 --> 00:04:53,640
dying is just increasing and increasing.

83
00:04:54,040 --> 00:04:58,920
Okay? The third problem is fertility.

84
00:05:00,460 --> 00:05:04,820
So right now, the fertility
rate in Russia is 1.5.

85
00:05:04,980 --> 00:05:07,500
That is below the replacement level.

86
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:11,420
Right? Remember that the replacement
level for society is 2.1.

87
00:05:12,160 --> 00:05:13,540
Russia is 1.5.

88
00:05:13,540 --> 00:05:16,520
But probably you have a lot of
men dying because of alcoholism.

89
00:05:16,620 --> 00:05:18,340
Okay? So since the year 2000,

90
00:05:18,840 --> 00:05:23,880
the population in Russia
has been declining steadily.

91
00:05:24,740 --> 00:05:26,780
And all this means is that

92
00:05:26,780 --> 00:05:29,640
if current trends continue,

93
00:05:30,100 --> 00:05:34,680
then Russia will cease
to exist as a society.

94
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:36,880
Okay? The nation will die.

95
00:05:38,220 --> 00:05:40,100
So why is this happening?

96
00:05:40,460 --> 00:05:43,420
Well, okay. The Western explanation is,

97
00:05:43,420 --> 00:05:45,440
is that this is happening because

98
00:05:46,300 --> 00:05:47,800
Russia is not democratic.

99
00:05:48,660 --> 00:05:52,000
Right? If you have full democracy and

100
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:53,800
you unleash the human potential

101
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:57,340
of your people, then

102
00:05:57,340 --> 00:05:59,860
Russia will prosper.

103
00:06:00,940 --> 00:06:04,380
But Putin, Vladimir Putin,
has a different explanation.

104
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:08,640
Okay? His explanation is that
this is happening to Russia.

105
00:06:08,920 --> 00:06:11,480
Okay? Corruption,
alcoholism, and low fertility

106
00:06:11,480 --> 00:06:16,140
because Russians have been lied to,

107
00:06:16,300 --> 00:06:17,540
deceived,

108
00:06:18,480 --> 00:06:21,980
and manipulated by Western civilization.

109
00:06:23,140 --> 00:06:29,080
Western civilization preaches
the gospel of liberal democracy,

110
00:06:29,420 --> 00:06:33,280
of freedom, of human
rights, of consumerism.

111
00:06:33,500 --> 00:06:36,300
And these are all lies.

112
00:06:36,540 --> 00:06:40,800
They're hypocrisies that have
fooled the Russian people

113
00:06:41,780 --> 00:06:44,560
and have corrupted the Russian soul

114
00:06:44,560 --> 00:06:47,560
and destroyed Russian civilization.

115
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:52,080
And because Russians are
abandoning their soul,

116
00:06:52,300 --> 00:06:53,740
their civilization, their nation,

117
00:06:53,940 --> 00:06:57,440
this is why this is happening.

118
00:06:57,780 --> 00:07:00,580
Okay? Does that make sense?
That is Putin's argument.

119
00:07:01,380 --> 00:07:03,680
So why does Putin believe this?

120
00:07:03,780 --> 00:07:06,900
Well, in the late 80s,

121
00:07:06,900 --> 00:07:10,420
the Soviet Union had
basically lost the Cold War.

122
00:07:10,420 --> 00:07:14,140
And they lost the Cold War because
their elite basically gave up.

123
00:07:14,280 --> 00:07:15,720
They no longer believed in communism.

124
00:07:15,940 --> 00:07:19,340
They didn't believe in self
-sacrifice for the nation.

125
00:07:20,320 --> 00:07:22,000
They thought that Western values,

126
00:07:22,340 --> 00:07:25,240
the Western lifestyle was much better.

127
00:07:25,320 --> 00:07:29,580
Okay? So they gave up. In the late 80s,

128
00:07:30,240 --> 00:07:32,320
there was an American historian.

129
00:07:32,800 --> 00:07:35,340
He actually works for the
American State Department.

130
00:07:35,560 --> 00:07:37,300
And his name is Francis Fukuyama.

131
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:39,900
And he wrote an extremely

132
00:07:40,420 --> 00:07:43,300
influential essay called
The End of History.

133
00:07:44,500 --> 00:07:45,760
End of History.

134
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:47,900
Okay? With a quotation mark.

135
00:07:48,660 --> 00:07:50,500
And he argued that

136
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:53,840
the Soviet Union fell

137
00:07:54,300 --> 00:07:58,300
and America became triumphant
because liberal democracy

138
00:07:59,560 --> 00:08:02,680
is the best idea

139
00:08:03,180 --> 00:08:05,100
to have ever been invented.

140
00:08:07,040 --> 00:08:09,440
And to make his argument,

141
00:08:09,440 --> 00:08:12,540
he uses the philosopher Frederick Hegel.

142
00:08:12,620 --> 00:08:17,700
Okay? Now, Frederick Hegel had something
called the theory of the dialectic.

143
00:08:18,280 --> 00:08:21,140
Dialectic. And

144
00:08:21,140 --> 00:08:25,100
what Hegel argued is that history

145
00:08:26,180 --> 00:08:30,580
is determined by a war of ideas.

146
00:08:32,520 --> 00:08:37,300
The progress of history is
determined by the movement of ideas.

147
00:08:37,300 --> 00:08:40,740
And how ideas work is

148
00:08:40,740 --> 00:08:44,440
that they have a pattern
called the dialectic.

149
00:08:44,540 --> 00:08:46,260
Okay? So there's a thesis.

150
00:08:47,840 --> 00:08:50,620
A new idea comes into being.

151
00:08:51,360 --> 00:08:55,160
But then we recognize that
this idea has problems.

152
00:08:55,240 --> 00:08:57,080
It's too extreme. It's too problematic.

153
00:08:57,380 --> 00:08:59,000
So we create an antithesis.

154
00:08:59,300 --> 00:09:01,920
Okay? But

155
00:09:01,920 --> 00:09:06,080
this antithesis itself
is also too extreme.

156
00:09:06,180 --> 00:09:08,340
And this creates also problems. So then

157
00:09:08,340 --> 00:09:12,140
what happens is the thesis
and antithesis come together

158
00:09:12,140 --> 00:09:16,740
and create a more moderate,
more efficient idea.

159
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:18,200
Okay? Called the synthesis.

160
00:09:19,920 --> 00:09:21,860
And this is how

161
00:09:23,020 --> 00:09:25,540
history moves or progresses.

162
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:28,420
And so Fukuyama takes
this idea and says, okay,

163
00:09:28,620 --> 00:09:32,060
well this explains what's happening today.

164
00:09:32,300 --> 00:09:35,480
Where at first you have a
thesis called capitalism.

165
00:09:35,740 --> 00:09:38,920
Okay? Capitalism.

166
00:09:39,200 --> 00:09:40,920
And this creates the
industrial revolution.

167
00:09:41,180 --> 00:09:44,220
Right? And because
capitalism was too extreme,

168
00:09:44,480 --> 00:09:46,860
we move towards communism.

169
00:09:47,180 --> 00:09:48,820
Okay? Communism was created

170
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:53,160
to counteract the extremes of capitalism.

171
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:57,000
But communism itself is too extreme.

172
00:09:57,160 --> 00:09:59,480
So then we move towards the middle.

173
00:09:59,560 --> 00:10:01,580
Which is the right idea.

174
00:10:01,660 --> 00:10:06,040
Which is called liberal democracy.

175
00:10:09,220 --> 00:10:13,100
Okay? So what is liberal democracy? Well,

176
00:10:13,220 --> 00:10:18,840
at the core of liberal democracy
is the idea of consumerism.

177
00:10:20,940 --> 00:10:24,640
And the idea of consumerism
is that we exist

178
00:10:26,120 --> 00:10:27,940
to buy things.

179
00:10:28,560 --> 00:10:31,020
And as long as we buy things,

180
00:10:31,400 --> 00:10:33,100
there will be world peace.

181
00:10:33,420 --> 00:10:36,020
Why? Because consumers have
the right to buy things.

182
00:10:36,020 --> 00:10:37,860
And they have a need to buy. And therefore

183
00:10:37,860 --> 00:10:40,920
nations have a need to produce.

184
00:10:41,340 --> 00:10:43,720
And nations produce the best when

185
00:10:43,720 --> 00:10:47,540
they are trading together as opposed
to warring against each other.

186
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:51,700
Okay? So this is the argument

187
00:10:51,700 --> 00:10:57,360
that Francis Fukuyama makes
in the end of history.

188
00:10:59,820 --> 00:11:02,060
I want to explain this argument further.

189
00:11:02,260 --> 00:11:04,120
Okay? What's he really saying?

190
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:07,800
Okay. So throughout human history,

191
00:11:08,020 --> 00:11:10,800
all societies have
struggled with one problem.

192
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:12,800
Which is how do we optimize

193
00:11:13,700 --> 00:11:16,420
the workforce? How do we get each and

194
00:11:16,420 --> 00:11:19,980
every person to work as hard
as possible for our society?

195
00:11:22,700 --> 00:11:25,640
And if everyone did that,
then our society would be

196
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:28,120
strong, united, and prosperous.

197
00:11:28,300 --> 00:11:31,340
Right? Okay? So that's a
fundamental problem of politics.

198
00:11:32,380 --> 00:11:34,540
How do we optimize
workforce participation?

199
00:11:35,200 --> 00:11:39,500
And traditionally, or historically,
there have been three answers.

200
00:11:40,100 --> 00:11:41,340
The first is war.

201
00:11:42,240 --> 00:11:44,220
The second is religion.

202
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:47,720
And the third is civilization.

203
00:11:48,220 --> 00:11:53,580
Okay? Now,

204
00:11:54,380 --> 00:11:56,000
as you can understand,

205
00:11:56,540 --> 00:11:59,780
these three things work because they give

206
00:12:00,380 --> 00:12:04,520
structure, meaning,

207
00:12:05,160 --> 00:12:09,420
and purpose to our lives.

208
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:12,200
Okay? And we have structure,
meaning, and purpose,

209
00:12:12,340 --> 00:12:15,680
we are much more motivated to work hard.

210
00:12:16,540 --> 00:12:20,980
But as you can also see, there
are actually lots of problems

211
00:12:22,220 --> 00:12:23,840
with all three.

212
00:12:23,980 --> 00:12:25,700
Right? War is you kill people.

213
00:12:25,800 --> 00:12:28,020
That's bad. Religion is superstitious.

214
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:31,860
Okay? But civilization itself is also

215
00:12:32,380 --> 00:12:37,680
problematic. Because the larger
extreme of civilization is

216
00:12:38,640 --> 00:12:41,520
racism. Okay? Which

217
00:12:41,520 --> 00:12:44,660
is to say that we Russians
are better than everyone else.

218
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:46,480
We Chinese are better than everyone else.

219
00:12:46,740 --> 00:12:48,620
Therefore, we can do whatever we want.

220
00:12:48,760 --> 00:12:53,360
Okay? And this naturally
leads to imperialism. Right?

221
00:12:56,380 --> 00:13:00,280
We have a duty to go conquer other people,

222
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:01,600
to civilize them.

223
00:13:01,720 --> 00:13:03,360
Right? Something called
the white man's burden.

224
00:13:04,720 --> 00:13:06,920
And this leads to fascism.

225
00:13:07,080 --> 00:13:10,820
Okay? Okay?

226
00:13:10,860 --> 00:13:12,800
War and conquest are the ultimate good.

227
00:13:14,120 --> 00:13:17,520
So, historically, war,
religion, and civilization

228
00:13:18,140 --> 00:13:21,040
have given people structure,
meaning, and purpose,

229
00:13:21,360 --> 00:13:23,600
but they create a lot of problems.

230
00:13:23,720 --> 00:13:26,040
They create suffering, and war,

231
00:13:27,020 --> 00:13:28,440
and pain. Okay?

232
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:32,820
So, but over time,

233
00:13:33,200 --> 00:13:36,100
what has happened is that

234
00:13:37,560 --> 00:13:42,300
all of them, over time, have
become much more abstract.

235
00:13:43,660 --> 00:13:49,360
And the reason why they've become more abstract
is in order to increase the population,

236
00:13:49,620 --> 00:13:53,100
in order to create mass society.

237
00:13:53,520 --> 00:13:54,820
Okay? So, let me give
you an example of this.

238
00:13:55,180 --> 00:13:56,780
The earliest religions

239
00:13:57,480 --> 00:14:00,200
in humanity have been polytheistic.

240
00:14:01,200 --> 00:14:03,760
Okay? And the gods themselves
were very much like humans.

241
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:05,280
Think of the Greeks. Okay? Zeus,

242
00:14:07,260 --> 00:14:08,580
Athena, Hera.

243
00:14:08,860 --> 00:14:11,940
Okay? It was a polytheistic society, and

244
00:14:11,940 --> 00:14:14,760
they were very much like humans.

245
00:14:15,360 --> 00:14:16,620
But over time,

246
00:14:17,100 --> 00:14:21,020
this polytheism became monotheistic,
and it became abstract.

247
00:14:21,180 --> 00:14:24,920
Okay? The idea of God was
so much removed from us.

248
00:14:25,700 --> 00:14:28,020
And the benefit of that is that

249
00:14:28,020 --> 00:14:31,480
you can have more people
believing in one God.

250
00:14:32,620 --> 00:14:35,400
And it motivates you to work harder.

251
00:14:35,540 --> 00:14:37,280
Okay? It's just an abstract concept.

252
00:14:38,260 --> 00:14:40,020
And because of abstraction,

253
00:14:41,040 --> 00:14:42,980
we develop new ideas.

254
00:14:43,260 --> 00:14:45,240
For example, money.

255
00:14:45,380 --> 00:14:48,280
Okay? So,

256
00:14:48,320 --> 00:14:51,580
rather than have war, religion,

257
00:14:51,970 --> 00:14:55,220
and civilization as the structure

258
00:14:55,900 --> 00:14:59,520
and center of our society,
one would make money

259
00:15:00,280 --> 00:15:01,640
from the structure of your society. Okay?

260
00:15:01,840 --> 00:15:03,640
This is what we call capitalism.

261
00:15:05,440 --> 00:15:09,620
And capitalism, of course, led
to the industrial revolution.

262
00:15:10,100 --> 00:15:13,400
Industrialism. Okay?

263
00:15:13,500 --> 00:15:17,700
Capitalism meant that
societies were becoming

264
00:15:18,240 --> 00:15:20,280
wealthier and wealthier,
more industrialized.

265
00:15:21,340 --> 00:15:23,060
Okay? Does that make sense? Alright.

266
00:15:24,300 --> 00:15:28,520
But there's a problem
with capitalism. Right?

267
00:15:28,700 --> 00:15:34,340
What's the problem with making capital or
money at the very heart of your society?

268
00:15:46,480 --> 00:15:48,060
Exactly. Okay? So,

269
00:15:48,160 --> 00:15:51,420
the first major problem with
capitalism is it's all -consuming.

270
00:15:52,100 --> 00:15:54,440
So, as Jack says,

271
00:15:54,760 --> 00:15:57,880
all capitalism cares
about is the expansion and

272
00:15:57,880 --> 00:16:02,520
growth of capital, regardless
of its effect on society.

273
00:16:02,960 --> 00:16:05,100
Okay? Profit for the
sake of growing profit.

274
00:16:05,240 --> 00:16:08,300
It's an all -consuming idea, which

275
00:16:08,300 --> 00:16:11,480
can ultimately lead to the
destruction of the planet.

276
00:16:11,600 --> 00:16:12,860
Okay? That's the first problem.

277
00:16:13,040 --> 00:16:15,620
What's another problem with capitalism?

278
00:16:15,840 --> 00:16:20,160
Or the idea of having money as the
heart and center of your society?

279
00:16:25,560 --> 00:16:35,120
Anyone? Okay. So,

280
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:37,320
what this means is that

281
00:16:37,320 --> 00:16:40,080
money likes to consolidate itself.

282
00:16:40,540 --> 00:16:42,700
Okay? Consolidating. Okay? Meaning that

283
00:16:43,420 --> 00:16:47,120
if, so the example is, let's just say
that each of us had a million dollars.

284
00:16:47,280 --> 00:16:50,240
Right? What's the fastest
way for us to grow our money?

285
00:16:52,840 --> 00:16:55,840
If we put it together, right?
And then we go invest it.

286
00:16:57,200 --> 00:17:00,240
Okay? So, in other
words, if you just like,

287
00:17:00,280 --> 00:17:03,720
let capitalism do whatever
it wants to infinity,

288
00:17:04,360 --> 00:17:08,440
what happens is that you exactly
have one person with all the money.

289
00:17:08,980 --> 00:17:12,640
Okay? Does that make sense? Because that's the
fastest way to grow money, by consolidating it.

290
00:17:13,580 --> 00:17:16,820
Okay? So that's problematic.
What else is wrong with

291
00:17:17,600 --> 00:17:21,820
capitalism or money? Okay.

292
00:17:21,880 --> 00:17:24,980
So another problem is
the idea of alienating.

293
00:17:26,960 --> 00:17:28,000
Or dehumanizing.

294
00:17:32,680 --> 00:17:34,380
Okay? What does this mean?

295
00:17:36,020 --> 00:17:38,040
Capital alienates and dehumanizes.

296
00:17:39,060 --> 00:17:40,140
What does that mean?

297
00:17:48,060 --> 00:17:51,560
Exactly. Okay. You are, you
as a person cease to be human.

298
00:17:52,160 --> 00:17:54,320
Right? To be human is to be a complex,

299
00:17:55,540 --> 00:17:56,940
multifaceted individual

300
00:17:58,100 --> 00:17:59,580
who likes to create and love.

301
00:18:00,280 --> 00:18:03,560
But in capitalism, you're
only your production value,

302
00:18:03,860 --> 00:18:06,560
you're only the amount of
money in your bank account.

303
00:18:06,800 --> 00:18:08,480
Okay? Does that make sense? Alright?

304
00:18:08,680 --> 00:18:11,280
So, for all these reasons,

305
00:18:12,700 --> 00:18:15,140
capitalism is really bad.

306
00:18:15,300 --> 00:18:20,000
There are actually more
reasons. Okay? So, Karl Marx,

307
00:18:22,300 --> 00:18:26,400
in his Communist Manifesto, points
out all these problems of capitalism

308
00:18:26,400 --> 00:18:27,700
and he proposes a solution.

309
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:32,340
Which is, okay, rather than
make money at the heart

310
00:18:32,340 --> 00:18:34,820
and center of your industrial society,

311
00:18:35,200 --> 00:18:41,020
make the worker the heart

312
00:18:41,020 --> 00:18:42,760
and center of your society.

313
00:18:43,240 --> 00:18:45,780
Okay? So he makes this argument.

314
00:18:45,960 --> 00:18:49,620
But what's very revolutionary or prescient

315
00:18:50,230 --> 00:18:54,920
about his argument is
this is a natural cycle.

316
00:18:55,100 --> 00:18:59,800
Okay? This is part of the Hegel cycle
where capitalism comes along and

317
00:19:00,280 --> 00:19:01,560
capitalism will be the natural evolution

318
00:19:02,580 --> 00:19:04,500
of capitalism. Okay?

319
00:19:04,560 --> 00:19:07,100
Why? Okay.

320
00:19:07,100 --> 00:19:08,620
Okay. So let's do the thought experiment.

321
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:11,740
Okay? Let's do this thought experiment
where your parents have died

322
00:19:12,260 --> 00:19:17,180
and now you're working in a
factory in order to survive.

323
00:19:18,120 --> 00:19:20,840
How do you feel about this?

324
00:19:23,260 --> 00:19:25,960
Your parents have died.
There's no one to support you.

325
00:19:26,120 --> 00:19:29,820
So, at age 16, 17, 18, you
have to go off to a factory.

326
00:19:30,280 --> 00:19:31,760
To make money for yourself.

327
00:19:32,020 --> 00:19:33,320
So how do you feel about this?

328
00:19:37,220 --> 00:19:38,460
Are you happy about this?

329
00:19:39,580 --> 00:19:42,180
How, how do you feel?

330
00:19:46,060 --> 00:19:49,060
Depressing and? And lonely and?

331
00:19:53,640 --> 00:19:55,680
Yeah, exactly. You're bitter.

332
00:19:56,080 --> 00:19:57,600
And you're depressed.

333
00:19:58,100 --> 00:19:59,600
Okay? You're alienated.

334
00:20:00,580 --> 00:20:04,620
So then what do you do?
Then what do you do?

335
00:20:13,060 --> 00:20:16,080
What can you do now? You're bitter.

336
00:20:16,380 --> 00:20:18,300
You're angry. You're depressed.

337
00:20:18,700 --> 00:20:20,040
You're lonely. So what do you do?

338
00:20:26,900 --> 00:20:28,360
Okay. You start to

339
00:20:28,840 --> 00:20:30,260
think about why this is the case.

340
00:20:30,280 --> 00:20:33,300
Right? You start to have
a political consciousness.

341
00:20:33,740 --> 00:20:35,460
What Marx calls political

342
00:20:36,260 --> 00:20:40,620
consciousness. From this
alienation of the worker,

343
00:20:40,860 --> 00:20:43,600
workers will start to develop
a political consciousness.

344
00:20:43,960 --> 00:20:45,960
Right? They're like,
why is this happening?

345
00:20:46,420 --> 00:20:47,820
Why has the government abandoned me?

346
00:20:48,100 --> 00:20:49,680
Why has society abandoned me?

347
00:20:49,740 --> 00:20:50,980
What can I do about this?

348
00:20:51,160 --> 00:20:53,460
Okay? So then what happens?

349
00:20:56,240 --> 00:20:57,620
That's exactly right. You want change.

350
00:20:57,620 --> 00:20:59,420
Right? And how do you enact change?

351
00:21:03,440 --> 00:21:06,500
Yes. Okay. You spread your
ideas and you organize.

352
00:21:06,880 --> 00:21:10,440
Right? And when you organize,
what do you realize?

353
00:21:17,200 --> 00:21:20,980
Yeah. What you recognize
when you start to organize is

354
00:21:21,410 --> 00:21:24,020
the capitalist needs you to do the work.

355
00:21:24,440 --> 00:21:27,420
Right? The capitalist owns the capital and

356
00:21:27,420 --> 00:21:30,760
the factories, but you're the one
who's actually doing the real work.

357
00:21:31,160 --> 00:21:32,460
So without you,

358
00:21:33,380 --> 00:21:36,140
the factories can't run. So
as long as you stay united,

359
00:21:36,480 --> 00:21:41,100
you can enact whatever
political demands you want.

360
00:21:41,320 --> 00:21:42,620
Okay? Does that make sense? Okay?

361
00:21:42,720 --> 00:21:46,800
So for Marx, this is just a
natural evolution of capitalism.

362
00:21:47,100 --> 00:21:49,920
Capitalism leads to the
alienation of the working class,

363
00:21:50,160 --> 00:21:54,840
which will lead to their political consciousness,
which will lead to their solidarity,

364
00:21:55,280 --> 00:21:58,240
which will lead to a
political revolution, and

365
00:21:58,240 --> 00:22:02,860
so you can make the worker
as the heart and center

366
00:22:03,380 --> 00:22:04,960
of your society.

367
00:22:05,820 --> 00:22:08,960
Okay? Does that make sense, guys?

368
00:22:09,180 --> 00:22:12,520
Alright? Now,

369
00:22:12,520 --> 00:22:14,860
what's amazing about Marx

370
00:22:15,300 --> 00:22:18,260
is that today we say he's wrong.

371
00:22:18,480 --> 00:22:22,720
Right? Communism happened
in the Soviet Union,

372
00:22:22,880 --> 00:22:27,200
it happened in China, but it didn't
happen in Europe and in the United States.

373
00:22:27,620 --> 00:22:30,720
Where Marx said it would
happen first, because

374
00:22:30,720 --> 00:22:33,920
Germany was more industrialized
than Russia or China.

375
00:22:34,100 --> 00:22:36,660
Okay? Does that make
sense? That's what we say.

376
00:22:37,380 --> 00:22:39,800
If you think about it deeply, okay,

377
00:22:42,500 --> 00:22:45,880
Marx was right. After World War II,

378
00:22:46,860 --> 00:22:50,400
every society, every industrial
society, to some extent,

379
00:22:51,260 --> 00:22:54,620
adopted the ideals of communism.

380
00:22:55,560 --> 00:22:57,380
Does that make sense? Okay?

381
00:22:57,620 --> 00:23:00,240
We call this socialism, not communism, but

382
00:23:00,240 --> 00:23:03,080
basically it adhere to the thinking

383
00:23:03,740 --> 00:23:07,380
of Marx, which is to make
the worker the heart

384
00:23:07,380 --> 00:23:08,720
and center of your society.

385
00:23:09,420 --> 00:23:11,480
And why did they do
that after World War II?

386
00:23:13,860 --> 00:23:16,680
Exactly, okay? Because
workers create value.

387
00:23:20,020 --> 00:23:21,880
Money doesn't create any value.

388
00:23:22,180 --> 00:23:23,700
Money just creates more money.

389
00:23:23,820 --> 00:23:27,260
Okay, it's speculative. But
the workers create value.

390
00:23:27,620 --> 00:23:30,700
And therefore, you have to
treat your workers properly.

391
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:33,460
So, in America and in Europe,

392
00:23:33,640 --> 00:23:37,880
workers became the heart
and center of your society.

393
00:23:38,320 --> 00:23:41,020
And the workers through unions

394
00:23:41,500 --> 00:23:45,000
could demand political reforms.

395
00:23:45,560 --> 00:23:50,920
And so, all of society was geared towards
making the lives of the middle class,

396
00:23:51,240 --> 00:23:52,600
the working class, better, okay?

397
00:23:52,780 --> 00:23:54,660
That's why you had excellent healthcare,

398
00:23:55,200 --> 00:23:56,640
great public schools.

399
00:23:58,620 --> 00:24:02,900
Cheap universities. Okay?

400
00:24:03,020 --> 00:24:06,840
So, the 50s and 60s and
70s was basically the peak

401
00:24:09,300 --> 00:24:11,480
of society for the working class.

402
00:24:12,780 --> 00:24:14,240
But in the 80s,

403
00:24:16,020 --> 00:24:17,240
we started to change this.

404
00:24:17,280 --> 00:24:21,320
Why? Why would we want
to change the system?

405
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:23,260
It's a great system, right? Marx is right.

406
00:24:23,500 --> 00:24:27,540
Having the worker as the heart
and center of your society.

407
00:24:27,620 --> 00:24:30,620
As the central organizing unit of society

408
00:24:30,620 --> 00:24:35,960
makes a lot more sense than
having money as the heart

409
00:24:35,960 --> 00:24:39,660
and center, okay? But starting in the
80s, we start to go back to money.

410
00:24:39,780 --> 00:24:50,640
Why? Excuse me?

411
00:24:57,960 --> 00:25:02,420
Who wants more? Yes, exactly.

412
00:25:02,560 --> 00:25:05,180
So, what happened in the 80s is something
called the revolt of the elite.

413
00:25:08,680 --> 00:25:10,500
Okay? In other words,

414
00:25:11,100 --> 00:25:16,880
the problem with having a society based on
the worker is it becomes too egalitarian,

415
00:25:17,280 --> 00:25:19,340
too equal, right?

416
00:25:19,560 --> 00:25:22,920
But if you're like the elite,
you don't want equality,

417
00:25:23,400 --> 00:25:25,100
you want difference.

418
00:25:25,460 --> 00:25:27,600
You want to have the same values.

419
00:25:27,620 --> 00:25:30,040
You want to have power
and money in your hands.

420
00:25:30,200 --> 00:25:34,820
Does that make sense? So, the revolt
of the elite happened in the 80s.

421
00:25:34,860 --> 00:25:39,060
And this is what we call in the
United States the Reagan Revolution,

422
00:25:39,440 --> 00:25:40,980
okay? The Reagan Revolution.

423
00:25:42,040 --> 00:25:44,600
The beginning of neoliberalism,
free market capitalism.

424
00:25:45,040 --> 00:25:47,780
And in Britain it was
called Thatcherism, okay?

425
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:50,140
Margaret Thatcher. The
Thatcher Revolution.

426
00:25:51,380 --> 00:25:54,920
And so, now you need to transition

427
00:25:55,560 --> 00:25:59,480
away from the worker to
something else, okay?

428
00:25:59,580 --> 00:26:01,520
Another ideology that

429
00:26:01,520 --> 00:26:05,400
allows the elite to amass power, okay?

430
00:26:05,520 --> 00:26:09,200
So, just to show you how
radical this revolution was,

431
00:26:09,820 --> 00:26:11,420
in the 1970s, okay?

432
00:26:11,500 --> 00:26:15,140
In the 1970s, if you were a CEO,
the head of a company, okay?

433
00:26:15,420 --> 00:26:16,900
You were making on average

434
00:26:17,360 --> 00:26:19,500
one million US dollars a year.

435
00:26:19,640 --> 00:26:21,980
That's pretty good, right?
That's really good money.

436
00:26:23,380 --> 00:26:24,800
And that one million dollars

437
00:26:25,420 --> 00:26:27,100
was more than

438
00:26:27,620 --> 00:26:29,540
20 times the worker.

439
00:26:30,980 --> 00:26:33,980
Okay? And that's

440
00:26:34,880 --> 00:26:37,840
pretty reasonable. Today,

441
00:26:38,060 --> 00:26:41,320
the average CEO in the United States

442
00:26:41,320 --> 00:26:44,220
makes 20 million dollars a year.

443
00:26:44,560 --> 00:26:45,740
And that

444
00:26:45,740 --> 00:26:51,220
is 200 to 300 times more than the
average worker in the company.

445
00:26:51,420 --> 00:26:53,060
Does that make sense? So,

446
00:26:53,180 --> 00:26:57,220
in the 80s inequality started

447
00:26:57,620 --> 00:26:59,100
to explode.

448
00:27:00,260 --> 00:27:02,200
Right? And so, they're transitioning

449
00:27:02,760 --> 00:27:05,000
from the worker to a new

450
00:27:05,400 --> 00:27:07,120
organizing unit called the consumer.

451
00:27:10,500 --> 00:27:14,280
Okay? So, they needed to destroy

452
00:27:14,900 --> 00:27:16,860
the working class, the middle class.

453
00:27:17,240 --> 00:27:21,640
And the way they did it was by introducing
a new concept called the consumer, okay?

454
00:27:21,960 --> 00:27:25,780
So, in the 50s, 60s, and 70s, the
government promised you a good job.

455
00:27:25,900 --> 00:27:28,440
If you were a member of a
society if you were a citizen,

456
00:27:28,720 --> 00:27:31,080
I promise you a good job

457
00:27:31,700 --> 00:27:33,560
that you would have for
the rest of your life.

458
00:27:33,700 --> 00:27:36,100
Okay? So, in the 80s,

459
00:27:36,120 --> 00:27:39,480
the government said I promise you that

460
00:27:39,480 --> 00:27:43,560
you have low prices and a
wide selection of goods.

461
00:27:44,960 --> 00:27:46,180
Okay? Does that make sense?

462
00:27:47,660 --> 00:27:52,740
Alright? So, this sounds
like a subtle shift,

463
00:27:52,880 --> 00:27:55,440
going from the worker to the consumer.

464
00:27:55,600 --> 00:27:58,520
Okay? But what this meant was a revolution

465
00:27:59,320 --> 00:28:03,320
in society. A revolution in politics.

466
00:28:03,660 --> 00:28:06,980
So, remember that an
example of the worker,

467
00:28:07,200 --> 00:28:12,260
the worker has to have political consciousness
in order to protect his or her rights,

468
00:28:12,380 --> 00:28:14,740
in order to organize and unify

469
00:28:15,720 --> 00:28:19,440
and push for favorable political reforms.

470
00:28:19,560 --> 00:28:21,340
Okay? That's what the worker must do.

471
00:28:21,420 --> 00:28:24,440
Okay? But now let's think about
the mentality of the consumer.

472
00:28:24,740 --> 00:28:27,140
And to do this, let's do another

473
00:28:27,620 --> 00:28:29,900
thought experiment. And the
thought experiment is this.

474
00:28:30,380 --> 00:28:32,300
Everyone in the school, about 500 people,

475
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:38,420
I decide to give everyone
1 million US dollars.

476
00:28:38,900 --> 00:28:40,900
Okay? So, everyone in the school

477
00:28:41,500 --> 00:28:44,760
has exactly 1 million US dollars

478
00:28:45,380 --> 00:28:48,240
to spend. What happens now?

479
00:28:50,040 --> 00:28:51,500
Think about this. What happens now?

480
00:28:51,520 --> 00:28:57,020
Use your imagination. What happens?

481
00:28:57,620 --> 00:29:10,840
What's the first thing you do? What's the first
thing you do? I've given you a million dollars.

482
00:29:11,220 --> 00:29:16,820
What do you do with it? Well,

483
00:29:16,820 --> 00:29:18,300
the first thing you do
is buy something, right?

484
00:29:19,220 --> 00:29:23,000
What do you want to buy? A 1
million dollars is a lot of money.

485
00:29:24,180 --> 00:29:25,460
What do you want to buy, Nav?

486
00:29:28,680 --> 00:29:29,940
You buy a house. You buy a house, right?

487
00:29:30,100 --> 00:29:32,020
That's great. That's a great purchase.

488
00:29:32,280 --> 00:29:33,980
Then what do you do? Then what do you do?

489
00:29:37,420 --> 00:29:38,980
Then buy a house.

490
00:29:39,220 --> 00:29:41,080
Then buy furniture.

491
00:29:41,640 --> 00:29:45,280
Okay. First thing is Nav buys a house.

492
00:29:45,420 --> 00:29:49,740
Then what does he do? Buy furniture.

493
00:29:49,740 --> 00:29:51,280
Buy furniture. Then what does he do?

494
00:29:52,260 --> 00:29:53,900
There's something that he
must do that's very important.

495
00:29:53,900 --> 00:29:56,100
What does he buy the house?

496
00:29:56,200 --> 00:30:01,640
What does he want to do?
He wants to take pictures

497
00:30:01,640 --> 00:30:02,980
and post on social media.

498
00:30:03,460 --> 00:30:05,900
Right? So everyone sees
it on social media.

499
00:30:06,660 --> 00:30:09,440
Then you see this.

500
00:30:09,680 --> 00:30:14,240
Nav has this huge house in Beijing
with lots of fancy furniture.

501
00:30:14,560 --> 00:30:18,920
What do you do now? You
also want to buy a house.

502
00:30:19,020 --> 00:30:22,220
But what kind of house?
A bigger house, right?

503
00:30:22,320 --> 00:30:27,900
And then what do you do?
You also post pictures.

504
00:30:27,960 --> 00:30:30,500
You also post pictures, okay?
Then how do other people feel?

505
00:30:34,420 --> 00:30:35,860
You think this is funny, okay?

506
00:30:35,900 --> 00:30:38,620
But this happens all the time. So

507
00:30:38,620 --> 00:30:41,700
very quickly what happens in the school?

508
00:30:46,560 --> 00:30:49,660
And you all spend your money
and you all go into debt.

509
00:30:49,960 --> 00:30:53,340
Right? Because you're in
competition with each other.

510
00:30:53,900 --> 00:30:56,320
That's not the biggest thing. And one
million dollars is a lot of money but

511
00:30:56,320 --> 00:30:59,200
it's not enough to buy everything, right?

512
00:30:59,480 --> 00:31:04,960
So you go into debt. You borrow more money
to buy more things. And then what happens?

513
00:31:11,840 --> 00:31:17,120
And then what happens? How do
you guys feel about each other?

514
00:31:17,220 --> 00:31:19,020
Do you guys have lunch together?
Do you guys have dinner together?

